Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel!). Pop the wedges on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @oil{}, scatter over the @nigella seeds{1/2%tsp}, then season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Halve, peel and cut the @red onion{1} into 2cm wedges. Pop the onion wedges on a medium baking tray and add a quarter of the @korma curry paste{50%g}, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and mix well to coat. Halfway through the potato cooking time, bake the onions on the middle shelf of your oven until the onion wedges are tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125} and pop into a medium #bowl{}. Halve the @cucumber{1/2}(halved lengthways), then thinly slice one half widthways into half moons (we'll prep the rest in the next step). Pop the cucumber into the bowl with the tomatoes. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all) and add to the bowl. Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop and add to the bowl (careful it's spicy). Halve the @lemon{1/2} and add a squeeze of lemon juice to the bowl with the cucumber and tomatoes. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and mix well. Set aside.

Scoop out the seeds from the remaining cucumber and discard them. Chop the cucumber into 1cm wide strips, then chop into small pieces. Pop into a medium bowl. Pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked from stalks and roughly chopped) and roughly chop (discard the stalks) and add to the bowl with the chopped cucumber. Add half @low fat natural yoghurt{150%g} and a squeeze of lemon juice. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and mix together. Set aside.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, add the @lamb mince{300%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> Fry the lamb in batches if you need to.

When the lamb is cooked add the remaining korma paste to the pan. Mix well and cooking until piping hot. Remove from the heat and stir in the remaining yoghurt.

When everything is nearly ready, pop the @garlic and coriander naan{4} in the oven alongside the wedges until warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Divide the naans between plates, top with the lamb korma and onion, spoon over the raita and the @mango chutney{40}. Serve with the wedges and salad alongside. Enjoy!